subnative 08/08/2022 1:01 PM
Hey @everyone . My name is Milan. Happy to be on board. I truly believe the "secret" to successful navigation of financial markets is the basic understanding of the following two words: -Supply -Demand Day in and day out, I am analyzing supply and demand (support and resistance as many call them) levels on daily, weekly, and monthly time frames. I constantly have my eye on broader market conditions and potential catalysts, the fed calendar, inflationary data, commodities prices, bond yields, etc... I rarely do intraday trades. I am mainly a swing/position trader of indexes and mega-cap companies. I do not buy: penny stocks weekly contracts "meme" stocks crypto While everyone was dogpiling onto GME at 300, I was scaling into a large $KO position. Payed off handsomely once money flowed back into real equity and out of the hands of retail. Once you study the market for hours and hours a day, you start to develop a system, and you start to develop a gut. Always trust your gut. I doubled down on $TSLA against Micheal Burry when he disclosed his massive short position. Again, payed off handsomely after Tesla ran $100 upward. News is noise. I keep a daily journal of all my trades and thoughts regarding the market. What I did right, what I did wrong, and why I did what I did. Being able to manage your emotions is very important as well, this took me quite a bit of time... Anyway, I will provide trades that I see, when the setups present themselves or my personal alerts go off. If you want to know the "why" or the "how", you can message me any time. Whether or not you follow me is up to you. I don't provide exits. It's up to you to be responsible and take profit. Good luck out there, I look forward to growing with you all (edited)

@everyone I know it's a lot, but if you're confused about tomorrow, give this a read. My thesis going into the absolute Super Bowl of a trading session we have tomorrow. I have technical reasoning, and macroeconomic reasoning. In my opinion, both matter equally in this situation. That being said, here's why it's a super bowl: First and foremost, FOMC. Fed minutes. Powell gives us the brass tax on the much anticipated interest rate hike. There are several variables here alone: 0.75 BP is the projected increase. In this case, all is going according to plan, the Fed isn't getting too aggressive (they believe it's under control) and market likely begins it's climb. 1.00 BP increase is a very possible curveball. .25 over what's projected, which shows that the federal reserve is SERIOUS about curbing inflation (meaning they're worried about it). This also shows the Fed may raise rates beyond expectation next time too. Market will likely be scared of this. Will likely sell. OR, since the Fed is being so aggressive, the market may think "the Fed is committed to stopping inflation! Let's buy!" Several pieces to this puzzle. AAAAAND, not only are rates being decided upon, but Fed Chairman Powell is also giving his Summary of Economic Projections. Absorb that. The head of the largest financial institution in the world, the Federal Reserve, is giving his economic outlook. The market answers to that. Moving on. The US Dollar has been on a tear, but it is finally showing even the slightest signs of weakness, as $SPY/QQQ consolidate into a strong demand area, at the same exact time. A pullback on the dollar coincides with bounces on indexes. The dollar will also move sharply after FOMC. Ticker: $DXY Last but not least, we've got the ever-mighty 10 year bond yield. It has been soaring, along with the dollar. It is finally in an 11 year supply zone. Right ahead of FOMC. While the indexes test what could be their last touches for the foreseeable future on these monster zones they've consolidated into. Ticker: TNX If the 10 year WERE to break above that zone, tech would suffer greatly, as would much of the market. These tech companies trade at very high P/E ratios, and an uncontrollable bond yield takes investors out of speculative assets (high P/E tech) and back into slow moving safer investment vehicles. The 10year caused a bear market about a year ago. $SPY: looks to bounce, tightening into a massive demand zone. $QQQ: refer to $SPY $DXY: slightly bearish, will make its move with powell $TNX: in massive supply, will make its move with powell TLDR: Tomorrow, the market comes to a fork in the road, ahead of heavy macroeconomic catalysts. @everyone These kinds of trading days, are the kind of trading days where as students, you really want to either be taking the smallest possible positions you can, or sitting out and taking actual note of how levels/catalysts are being approached and reacted to in this particular kind of market environment. You see how we're just kind of sloooooowly and gruelingly selling off through strong zones. Note this. Swing puts. Close at open for profit. Swing again. Small calls at big demand zones. Good morning @everyone. You guys are officially gonna think I'm nuts. I woke up, brushed my teeth, shaved, made myself what I call breakfast, and went through my pre-market checklist. Business as usual. I'm a macro economic enthusiast after all. This time however, I noticed one thing. One thing I never truly realized before: As I type this, we are taking part in what I believe to be once in a lifetime phase of overall market transition. Never seen anything like it. Can't find anything remotely similar to it back in the S&P500's chart either. If you've made it here you're in for a bit of a read. skip to the end for $SPY plan Anyway, hear me out. We are monitoring the market as it SHOWS us how money feels about the aforementioned transition. This is not the market it once was. 5 years ago, 10 years ago, 15 years ago. It's always changing, but the charts stayed more or less consistent. The past two years alone, this market has seen the coming and going of various "meme" stocks, NFTs, unlimited QE, inflation, rates, crypto, speculation, SPACs, IPOs, the biggest influx of retail traders in history, you name it. It all affected the market. The chart shows us all of it. It's easy to forget those events, they seem so long ago. The chart doesn't forget, though. In this current market, we are witnessing the Federal Reserve meticulously take steps to control the rescession that it printed itself into. More importantly, we are witnessing the market's reactions to this. The gamified intraday price action. The EOD 3 min to close squeezes in either direction. The fakeouts. The ascending quadruple top reacting strictly to fed meetings for a month and a half back at 395. Seemingly nonsensical price action at times. I haven't traded through events like black monday, the dotcom bubble, or '08. I do however believe we are currently in the next event that'll be talked about for decades to come. Take a look at this monthly chart of the S&P: (edited)

02:24

02:31
This. This is what's "weird". This shape. Almost every single trade I place is based on shapes in the chart. Sure, you might think I mean "candlestick patterns"... but when I look at a chart, I'm not trying to figure out what "pattern" what I'm seeing. I don't stick in the trade into some imaginary box I made up. There are a million different pattern names. When I look at a chart, I'm looking at the shape of everything on the larger time frame. For example. I was in short at 413. The $SPY daily was "a loose head and shoulders". That was my way of saying it looked weak, and that it did. We are now hanging around 397. So that leads us back to the shape. What's so weird about it? (edited)
